  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international efforts to address financial crimes\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. Major Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of standardized anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Expanded reporting obligations\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Risk-based compliance strategies\n- Advanced technology integration\n- Cryptocurrency and digital asset regulations\n- Enhanced customer identification procedures\n\n5. International Coordination\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Harmonized regulatory standards\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\n6. Emerging Trends\n- Artificial intelligence for detection\n- Machine learning-based monitoring\n- Blockchain tracking technologies\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership transparency\n\n7. Recent Developments\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency regulations\n- Stricter sanctions against financial crime\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve in response to emerging financial technologies and complex criminal strategies.",
